{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"939b95c5-6ddf-4597-8697-5fb832871b5f","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` tells the page not to add inset padding, but you likely still have the **navigation bar chrome** visible. You need to hide it separately, and ensure your image fills properly:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"\n             Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\">\n    <!-- or NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\" if using NavigationPage -->\n\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n           HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n           VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**Key things to check:**\n\n1. **Hide the nav bar** — `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` (Shell) or `NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"` (NavigationPage). The bar is a separate UI element; `SafeAreaEdges` doesn't remove it.\n\n2. **`Aspect=\"AspectFill\"`** — without this, the image keeps its native size and won't stretch to fill.\n\n3. **Android status/nav bar transparency** — .NET 10 makes Android apps edge-to-edge by default, but if the system bars are opaque, content draws behind them invisibly. Ensure translucent bars via your theme or `Window.StatusBarColor`/`Window.NavigationBarColor` set to transparent.\n\n4. **iOS** — `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` is the correct approach on iOS; just make sure no parent layout is adding its own margin/padding.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ce23eb2b-400d-4536-b968-8ad6b8a37857","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"No relevant content in this repo. Let me answer from my knowledge about .NET MAUI's edge-to-edge support in .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET 10, MAUI introduced edge-to-edge display by default on Android (following Android 15's requirements). The key APIs are:\n\n1. `SafeAreaEdges` on `ContentPage` - controls which edges respect safe areas. Setting to `None` means the page content should extend behind system bars.\n\n2. But there's also `IgnoreSafeArea` on individual views - this is important for making specific views extend into the safe area insets.\n\n3. On Android, apps targeting Android 15+ are edge-to-edge by default, but the system applies insets. MAUI's `SafeAreaEdges` controls how these insets are handled at the page level.\n\n\nThough setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` should prevent the page from adding padding, there might be other sources of that padding—like a `NavigationPage` or `Shell` adding its own navigation bar, or iOS applying additional safe area handling on top of the page-level setting.\n\nThe real issue is likely that they also need to hide the navigation bar itself using `NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"` or `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"`, since those UI elements are rendered separately from the safe area padding. On Android with .NET 10, edge-to-edge rendering is the default, but the system still applies window insets that need to be accounted for. I'll focus on the key steps they need to implement.","outputTokens":1137,"requestId":"DC09:243EE1:1E351F7:227CB57:69F54DA2"},"id":"0e84e966-1f5c-4465-a768-13a7080167db","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:05:00.351Z","parentId":"a52d11f9-3b2a-428b-a00e-d68dc4457ef2"}
